alternatives.transcript: Buenos días Maria how are you doing today...

utterances.transcript: Buenos días, Maria. How are you doing today?
I am good. I practice the words but I have difficulty with the subjunctive.
That's great that you practiced! The subjunctive can be tricky. Let's work on that today. First, let me ask - did you have any questions from the homework?
Yes. I have seen the examples yesterday but I don't understand nothing about when to use it.

I notice two things there. First, we say I saw the examples yesterday, not I have seen yesterday. Present perfect doesn't go with specific past times. Second, in English we say I don't understand anything, not nothing. That's a double negative.
Ah, I understand. In Spanish we use double negatives but in English no. I saw the examples yesterday. Is that correct?
Perfect! Excellent job. You learn very quickly. Now, let's practice some restaurant vocabulary. Imagine we're at a restaurant in Madrid.
Buenas tardes. ¿Mesa para cuántos?
Buenas tardes. Una mesa para two... para dos personas, por favor.
Muy bien. Good job correcting yourself! Síganme, por favor. Aquí tienen el menú.
Gracias. Eh... ¿Qué me recomienda? I want to try something typical.
Try to stay in Spanish! You can say Quiero probar algo típico. Can you repeat that?
Quiero probar algo típico.
¡Excelente! Le recomiendo la paella valenciana. Es nuestra especialidad. Also, we have patatas bravas which are very popular.
I would like the paella, please. And also the potatoes bravas... I mean, las patatas bravas.
Good self-correction! In Spanish, remember to say Me gustaría instead of I would like. So: Me gustaría la paella, por favor.
Me gustaría la paella, por favor. Y también las patatas bravas.
¡Perfecto! ¿Y para beber? What would you like to drink?
Eh... a wine red, please. I mean, un vino tinto.
That's a common mistake! In English we say red wine with the adjective before the noun. But you caught yourself - that's excellent. In Spanish it's vino tinto with the adjective after.
Yes, the adjective order is bery... very difficult for me.
I noticed you said bery instead of very. That's a common pronunciation issue for Spanish speakers. The B and V sounds are different in English. Try: very, with your teeth on your lip.
Vvvery. Very difficult.
Much better! You're making excellent progress. Now let's continue with our restaurant practice. How would you ask for the bill in Spanish?
La cuenta, por favor.

Perfect! You remember that well. Let me give you a summary of what we covered today. We worked on the present perfect versus simple past tense, double negatives, restaurant vocabulary, and adjective order. You're making great progress!
Thank you very much! I learned a lot today. See you next week.
¡Hasta la próxima semana! Great work today, Maria. Keep practicing!
